üìÑ Credit Memo ‚Äì Transaction Operations (Revolving Period)

During the revolving period, the facility operates as a fully secured, daily-monitored inventory financing platform supporting Auto1 Group SE‚Äôs vehicle trading activities.  The Issuer (Auto1 Funding B.V.) issues Senior, Mezzanine and Junior Notes and on-lends proceeds to Auto1 European Cars B.V. (‚ÄúCarCo‚Äù) to fund the purchase of eligible vehicles.  CarCo acts as borrower, servicer and collateral owner, with all sale proceeds from financed vehicles swept daily into pledged collection accounts held under the control of Cr√©dit Agricole CIB (Agent and Security Trustee).  Drawdowns are governed by a dynamic Borrowing-Base test referencing eligible inventory value, and any deficiencies are required to be cured within five business days.  Principal collections from vehicle disposals are ordinarily re-advanced to fund new eligible purchases, preserving revolving status until the scheduled revolving end date or an early-amortisation trigger.  Liquidity and operational resilience are supported through fully-funded reserve accounts (‚âà2% of outstanding balances) and a comprehensive security package over all assets, accounts and intercompany receivables.  This construct provides transparent collateral coverage, daily cash-flow visibility and strong structural controls consistent with senior secured warehouse standards.


Certainly ‚Äî here‚Äôs a concise, credit-committee‚Äìready section describing the credit enhancement structure of the Auto1 Inventory ABS under the 7th Amendment.
It‚Äôs written in the analytical tone of an internal credit memo or transaction approval note, highlighting both composition and risk-mitigation rationale.

‚∏ª

üìÑ Credit Enhancement

Credit enhancement (‚ÄúCE‚Äù) in the Auto1 Inventory Facility is provided through a combination of structural subordination, overcollateralisation, and liquidity reserves, ensuring the Senior Notes are protected from losses arising from asset under-performance or timing mismatches.  The transaction employs a three-tier capital structure‚ÄîSenior, Mezzanine and Junior tranches‚Äîfunded through inter-company loans from the Issuer to CarCo, with full subordination of Mezzanine and Junior amounts to the Senior facility both in the payment waterfall and in enforcement.

At the collateral level, the facility maintains dynamic overcollateralisation through the Borrowing-Base mechanism.  The aggregate principal advanced under the Senior and Mezzanine loans may not exceed the Net Borrowing Base, defined as the lower of (i) the aggregate value of eligible vehicles, adjusted for haircuts, and (ii) concentration-limited exposures net of reserves.  This ensures continuous asset coverage and automatically traps excess proceeds as the portfolio seasonally fluctuates.  Any Borrowing-Base deficiency must be cured within five business days through cash repayment, vehicle substitution, or Auto1 corporate top-up, thereby preventing structural erosion of enhancement.

Further CE is provided via liquidity and reserve accounts.  The Issuer Liquidity Reserve (1.0% of Senior Notes) and the CarCo Liquidity Reserve (0.75% of total loans) ensure timely payment of interest and senior fees under stress scenarios, while a dedicated Tax and Operating Reserve (0.25%) covers non-credit operational outflows.  Collections are swept daily to pledged accounts under the control of Cr√©dit Agricole CIB, eliminating commingling exposure and ensuring rapid deleveraging upon trigger events.  The transaction is also supported by a corporate undertaking from Auto1 Group SE, which can fund temporary shortfalls or cure Borrowing-Base breaches.

Certainly ‚Äî here‚Äôs a credit-memo-style section describing the eligibility criteria and performance triggers in the Auto1 Inventory Facility, aligned with the latest (7th Amendment) structure and written for a senior-lender audience.

‚∏ª

üìÑ Eligibility Criteria and Performance Triggers

The transaction applies a comprehensive set of eligibility criteria to ensure that only high-quality, liquid vehicle assets are funded through the structure.  Eligible Vehicles must be (i) wholly owned by Auto1 European Cars B.V. (CarCo), (ii) free and clear of any prior liens, and (iii) physically located within approved jurisdictions.  Vehicles must be passenger cars or light commercial vehicles with verifiable VINs, supported by full title documentation and insured under the Auto1 Group master policy.  Additional constraints limit the portfolio‚Äôs risk composition: vehicles must (a) not exceed a specified maximum age or mileage threshold, (b) comply with concentration caps by make, model, and country, and (c) be sold through recognised Auto1 sales channels within defined holding-period limits (typically 180 days).  Non-performing or ineligible vehicles (e.g. stolen, damaged, repossessed or unsold beyond threshold days-in-stock) are automatically excluded from the Borrowing-Base calculation, with CarCo required to cure any resulting deficiency within five business days through cash repayment, substitution, or additional collateral.

To maintain structural integrity during the revolving period, the facility is governed by a defined set of performance triggers designed to transition the deal into amortisation before material deterioration occurs.  These include:
	‚Ä¢	Borrowing-Base Deficiency Trigger: failure to cure a shortfall between net eligible inventory value and outstanding loans within five business days.
	‚Ä¢	Cash Trading Margin Trigger: breach of minimum rolling three-month gross margin (typically 5%) signalling weakening resale performance.
	‚Ä¢	Vehicle Turnover Trigger: excessive proportion of vehicles breaching the maximum stocking-day threshold.
	‚Ä¢	Operational Triggers: default, downgrade or replacement failure of the Servicer or key Auto1 Group entities.
	‚Ä¢	Corporate Trigger: unapproved change of control of Auto1 Group SE.

Breach of any of the above results in an Early Amortisation Event, immediately terminating new utilisations and switching the transaction into the controlled amortisation phase.  During this phase, all sale proceeds are applied daily towards sequential repayment of the Senior and Mezzanine loans.  These eligibility and trigger mechanisms collectively enforce ongoing asset quality, alignment of interests, and proactive deleveraging‚Äîhallmarks of a high-control, investment-grade inventory ABS platform.


Collectively, these layers‚Äîsubordination, dynamic overcollateralisation, daily cash control, and funded reserves‚Äîprovide a robust multi-channel enhancement framework that protects the Senior facility from both credit and liquidity shocks, aligning the structure with investment-grade securitisation standards.


Excellent ‚Äî here‚Äôs a credit-memo‚Äìgrade summary of the Events of Default and Servicer Termination Events as defined in the Auto1 Inventory ‚Äì 7th Amendment ‚Äì Amended & Restated MDCTA (15 Sep 2025) and cross-referenced loan agreements (Senior, Mezz, Junior).
This focuses on what each means, how it escalates, and how it affects the Senior Lenders‚Äô position.

‚∏ª

üìÑ Events of Default (EoDs)

(MDCTA Art. III ‚Äì ‚ÄúCarCo Events of Default‚Äù & ‚ÄúIssuer Events of Default‚Äù)

The structure distinguishes between Issuer-level and CarCo-level defaults, but both ultimately empower the Security Trustee (Cr√©dit Agricole CIB) to enforce the security package and trigger sequential repayment.

üîπ Issuer Events of Default

Triggered if any of the following persist beyond applicable grace periods:
	1.	Non-Payment: failure to pay interest, principal, or fees under the Notes or inter-company loans within 5 Business Days of due date.
	2.	Breach of Obligation: material covenant or undertaking breach (including reporting, negative pledge, maintenance of security) not remedied within 15 Business Days after notice.
	3.	Misrepresentation: materially false or misleading representation remaining uncorrected after 10 Business Days.
	4.	Invalidity of Security: all or substantial part of Issuer security becomes invalid or unenforceable.
	5.	Insolvency or Restructuring: Issuer becomes insolvent, files for bankruptcy, liquidation, or composition with creditors.
	6.	Illegality: any Transaction Document becomes illegal for the Issuer to perform.

Upon an Issuer EoD, the Security Trustee may (i) declare the Notes immediately due and payable and (ii) enforce all pledged rights over the CarCo Loans and related accounts.

‚∏ª

üîπ CarCo Events of Default

More operational in nature; typically precede Issuer enforcement:
	1.	Non-Payment: failure to pay interest or principal under any CarCo Loan within 5 Business Days.
	2.	Breach of Representations or Covenants: material inaccuracy or non-compliance not cured within 15 Business Days.
	3.	Invalid Security: loss of perfection or ranking of the CarCo Security.
	4.	Insolvency / Business Suspension: bankruptcy, liquidation filing, cessation of substantially all operations, or appointment of administrator.
	5.	Unlawfulness: performance of obligations becomes unlawful.
	6.	Failure to Maintain Authorisations / Insurance: lapse of licences, permits, or mandatory insurance coverage.
	7.	Cross-Default: default on other material financial indebtedness of CarCo or Auto1 Group above the defined threshold.

If a CarCo EoD occurs and is continuing, the Agent (CACIB) can block further utilisations, sweep all collections to repay outstanding loans, and instruct the Security Trustee to enforce.

‚∏ª

üìÑ Servicer Termination Events (STEs)

(MDCTA Art. V ‚Äì ‚ÄúServicing and Administration‚Äù)
These govern when Auto1 Group SE, acting as Servicer, can be replaced or backup-servicing activated.

üîπ Key Servicer Termination Events
	1.	Failure to Transfer Collections: delay > 2 Business Days in remitting funds to pledged accounts on two or more occasions in any 12-month period.
	2.	Failure to Provide Reports: missing or materially inaccurate Monthly or Daily Borrowing-Base Reports not corrected within 5 Business Days.
	3.	Breach of Servicing Standards: failure to perform duties in accordance with agreed standards (care of a prudent dealer) not cured within 10 Business Days after notice.
	4.	Misrepresentation: materially incorrect Servicer representation outstanding > 10 Business Days.
	5.	Insolvency / Change of Control: Servicer insolvency, bankruptcy, or unapproved change of control of Auto1 Group SE.
	6.	Rating / Performance Deterioration: downgrade of Servicer below the minimum short-term rating (typically A-2/P-2/F2) combined with failure to implement a Commingling Reserve or backup-servicer activation within 30 days.

üîπ Consequences
	‚Ä¢	CACIB (as Agent) may issue a Servicer Termination Notice.
	‚Ä¢	A Backup Servicer Activation Notice is then served, transferring data and cash-management rights to the designated backup (Autorola A/S).
	‚Ä¢	If the Servicer defaults permanently, the Security Trustee formally appoints the Backup Servicer to perform all collection and reporting functions.
	‚Ä¢	Persistent STEs escalate to an Issuer Early Amortisation Event if replacement is not completed within 45 days.

‚∏ª

üí° Credit View
	‚Ä¢	The EoDs give investors full enforcement rights‚Äîstandard for senior-secured ABS.
	‚Ä¢	The STEs act as operational early-warning triggers, ensuring that Auto1‚Äôs servicing failures or distress are addressed well before cash-flow disruption.
	‚Ä¢	Combined with daily cash sweeps and perfected security, they provide strong continuity of servicing and control even under borrower or servicer stress.



