Here‚Äôs a tight hedging blurb you can drop into the memo:

Hedging (rate & FX). The structure requires non-speculative hedging to stabilise cashflows. Interest-rate risk on the floating notes/loans (1-month EURIBOR) is covered via Required Hedging‚Äîtypically an interest-rate cap sized to outstanding notes (and re-benchmarked over time). Cap premia/periodic amounts are paid via the issuer waterfall, and failure to maintain the hedge is a documented trigger that can force remedial action or early amortisation. FX risk is ring-fenced operationally and contractually: SEK sales convert to EUR at ECB payment-date rates; other foreign-currency sales (e.g., PLN) settle at the hedge rate under an FX Trading Agreement. Reserved FX receivables run on tight clocks and low caps so unhedged exposure cannot build. All hedging agreements are pledged to the Security Trustee; downgrade-and-replace language and CSA collateralisation mitigate counterparty risk, and any hedge termination amounts are handled within the senior part of the waterfall.
